(b) Using the variable describing the chocolate percentage for each review, create a new column that groups chocolate percentages into one of four groups: (i)* \(<60 \%\), (ii) \(\geq 60\%\) to \(<70\%\), (iii) \(\geq 70 \%\) to \(\leq 90 \%\), and (iii) \(\geq 90 \%\).

(Hint check out the substr() function in base R and the case_when() function from dplyr see example below).

tmp <- substr(chocolate.cobo_geq_50$cocoa_percent,1,2)
chocolate.cobo_geq_50$cocoa_percent_discrete <-
  case_when(
  tmp < 60 ~ "<60%",
  tmp >= 60 & tmp < 70 ~ ">=60% to <70%",
  tmp >= 70 & tmp < 90 ~ ">=70% to <90%",
  tmp >= 90 ~ ">=90%"
  ) %>%
  factor()

levels(chocolate.cobo_geq_50$cocoa_percent_discrete)
## [1] "<60%"          ">=60% to <70%" ">=70% to <90%" ">=90%"

(c) Using the new column described in #2, re-order the factor levels (if needed) to be starting with the smallest percentage group and increasing to the largest percentage group (Hint check out the fct_relevel() function from forcats).

chocolate.cobo_geq_50$cocoa_percent_discrete <- 
  chocolate.cobo_geq_50$cocoa_percent_discrete %>%
  fct_relevel(sort)

levels(chocolate.cobo_geq_50$cocoa_percent_discrete)
## [1] "<60%"          ">=60% to <70%" ">=70% to <90%" ">=90%"

Part 2. Join two datasets together

2.0. Load gapminder data

gapminder.data <- unique(gapminder::gapminder[, c("country", "continent")])

2.1. Merge gapminder$continent to chocolate dataset

Use this dataset it to create a new column called continent in our chocolate dataset that contains the continent name for each review where the country of bean origin is.

Also manually add continents that have not been matched.

# create copy of raw dataframe
chocolate.with_cont <- chocolate

# standardize spelling of certain countries in chocolate.with_cont.country_of_bean_origin
chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin <-
  case_when(
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in% c("Trinidad", "Tobago") ~ "Trinidad and Tobago",
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in% c("Sao Tome", "Principe", "Sao Tome & Principe") ~ "Sao Tome and Principe",
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in% c("Congo", "DR Congo") ~ "Congo, Dem. Rep.",
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in% c("U.S.A.", "USA") ~ "United States",
    .default = as.character(chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin)
  )

# join chocolate with gapminder.data by country
chocolate.with_cont <- left_join(chocolate.with_cont, gapminder.data, 
                       join_by(country_of_bean_origin == country))

# manually add continents to chocolate for countries not listed in gapminder.data
chocolate.with_cont$continent <-
  case_when(
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in% 
      c("Belize", "Grenada", "Martinique", "St. Lucia", "St.Vincent-Grenadines", "Suriname") ~ "Americas",
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in%
      c("Burma", "Sumatra", "Sulawesi") ~ "Asia",
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in%
      c("Ivory Coast") ~ "Africa",
    chocolate.with_cont$country_of_bean_origin %in%
      c("Fiji", "Papua New Guinea", "Vanuatu", "Solomon Islands", "Samoa") ~ "Oceania",
    .default = as.character(chocolate.with_cont$continent)
  )

Part 3. Convert Wide Data into Long Data

3.1. Create an indicator column for each ingredient

Create a new set of columns titled beans, sugar, cocoa_butter, vanilla, letchin, and salt that contain a 1 or 0 representing whether or not that review for the chocolate bar contained that ingredient (1) or not (0).

# convert missing ingredient cell to empty string
chocolate$ingredients[is.na(chocolate$ingredients)] <- " "

# create ingredient columns
chocolate.with_ingredients <- 
  chocolate %>%
  mutate(
    beans = str_detect(ingredients, "B"),
    cocoa_butter = str_detect(ingredients, "C"),
    vanilla = str_detect(ingredients, "V"),
    letchin = str_detect(ingredients, "L"),
    salt = str_detect(ingredients, "Sa"),
    sugar = str_detect(ingredients, "S")
  )

3.2. Create an indicator column for each characteristic

Create a new set of columns titled char_cocoa, char_sweet, char_nutty, char_creamy, char_roasty, char_earthy that contain a 1 or 0 representing whether or not that the most memorable characteristic for the chocolate bar had that word (1) or not (0). For example, if the word sweet appears in the most_memorable_characteristics, then record a 1, otherwise a 0 for that review in the char_sweet column (Hint: check out str_detect() from the stringr package).

chocolate.with_ingredients <- 
  chocolate.with_ingredients %>%
  mutate(
    char_cocoa = str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "cocoa"),
    char_sweet = str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "sweet"),
    char_nutty = str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "nutty"),
    char_creamy = str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "creamy"),
    char_roasty = str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "roasty"),
    char_earthy = str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "earthy")
  )

3.4. Convert wide dataset to long

Convert this wide dataset into a long dataset with a new feature and mean_score column.

table.mean_ingredients_by_year.long <-
  pivot_longer(table.mean_ingredients_by_year,
               cols = beans:char_earthy,
               names_to = "ingredient",
               values_to = "mean_score") %>%
  as.tibble()

table.mean_ingredients_by_year.long$ingredient <-

Part 4. Data Visualization

4.1 - 4.4. Visualize changes in chocolate composition over the years

Use the functions in ggplot2 package to make a scatter plot of the mean_scores (y-axis) over time (x-axis). One point for each mean_score. For full credit, your plot should include:

1) An overall title for the plot and a subtitle summarizing key trends that you found. Also include a caption in the figure with your name.

2) Both the observed points for the mean_score, but also a smoothed non-linear pattern of the trend

3) All plots should be shown in the one figure

4) There should be an informative x-axis and y-axis label

table.mean_ingredients_by_year.long %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = review_date, y = mean_score, color = ingredient)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(
    method = "loess",
    se = FALSE
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ingredient) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "How have chocolate ingredients and characteristics change over time?",
       subtitle = "Based on review data from 2006 to 2021",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Proportion of bars with feature")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Josh: Overall, it seems that over the years, less letchin and vanilla are being included in chocolate bars. Cocoa butter has seen as small dip in popularity, but not as pronounced as that of letchin and vanilla. Beans and sugar are, by far, the most popular chocolate ingredient, with nearly every bar including them in their ingredient profile.

Josh: Here are the customizations I made.

  1. aes(x = factor(country_of_bean_origin), fill = factor(review_date), y = rating): I created a boxplot with country_of_bean_origin on the x-axis, rating on the y-axis, and review_date as the fill variable. There are 34 countries, and 16 review dates, so the plot will contain 34 * 16 = 544 boxes (assuming there is data for every country-year combo). This will be useful for making a great data visualization because it will allow me to easily toggle how I define my x, y, and fill variables.

  2. geom_boxplot() This customization created a boxplot from my ggplot object. I think this method of creating a boxplot is particularly useful because it is so easy to customize.

  3. facet_wrap(~review_date) I used this to create 16 facets, each defined by a specific year between 2006 and 2021. This customization is useful for separating visualizations by groups and makes it easier to see relationships within groups.

  4. axis.title.y = element_text(size = 5) I made the y-axis label have a font-size of 5. This makes it very small and therefore difficult to read. A better plot would have a larger font size.

  5. axis.title.x = element_text(size = 5) I also made the x-axis label have a font-size of 5. Again, a better plot would have a larger font size.

  6. panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "blue") This changed the color of the grid lines on each facet. Not really necessary for this plot, but could be necessary if the analyst wants to make it easier to read coordinates on the plot.

  7. plot.background = element_rect(fill = "red") Makes the canvas red. This is completely unnecessary for this plot, and makes it look quite ugly. I suppose this specification could be useful if someone wants to adjust the contrast between their plot and the canvas.

  8. plot.title = element_text(size = 25) I made the title have a font-size of 25. This is simply too large for this already overloaded plot. A better visualization would use a smaller font size for the title.

6.1 - 6.2. Improve a plot

The goal is to take my sad looking plot and make it better!

Josh: Ive reposted the original plot for reference:

chocolate %>%
    ggplot(aes(
        x = as.factor(review_date),
        y = rating,
        fill = review_date
    )) +
    geom_violin()

Josh: And here is my new-and-improved plot.

chocolate %>%
  ggplot(aes(
      x = as.factor(review_date),
      y = rating
    )) +
  geom_half_violin(position = position_nudge(x = -0.15), fill = "chocolate") +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.5, width = 0.075, alpha = 0.35) +
  labs(title = "Chocolate ratings become less variable over time",
       subtitle = "A visualization of chocolate ratings by year of review (from 2006 to 2021)",
       caption = "Created by Josh Stim using `gghalves` and `ggplot2`") +
  xlab("Year of Review") +
  ylab("Rating") +
  theme_bw(base_family = "Times", base_size = 15) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size = 18, vjust = -2),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 18, vjust = 2),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12),
        plot.caption = element_text(size = 9, vjust = -5),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 20, vjust = 2),
        plot.margin = unit(c(0.2, 0.2, 0.2, 0.2), "inches"))

Josh: I made the following customizations:

  1. geom_half_violin(position = position_nudge(x = -0.15), fill = "chocolate", scale = "area", trim = TRUE) Violin plots are redundant, in that they show the same density twice. I decided to use a half-violin plot (from library gghalves), which is exactly what it sounds like: it allows you to plot only half of the violin. I also nudged each half-violin 0.15 x-units to the left and colored all of them the same color (having different colors is unnecessary and might cause confusion).

  2. geom_jitter(size = 0.5, width = 0.075, alpha = 0.35) I also wanted to plot the individual data points within each year, so the viewer could get a better idea of how many points were within each year. I adjusted the size of the points, the width of the jitter, and made the points translucent by setting alpha = 0.35.

  3. labs(title = "Chocolate ratings become less variable over time", subtitle = "A visualization of chocolate ratings by year of review (from 2006 to 2021)", caption = "Created by Josh Stim using the gghalves and ggplot2") Created an informative title and subtitle for the plot. Also created a caption to document who created the visualization, and with what R packages.

  4. theme_bw(base_family = "Times", base_size = 15) I really like the theme_bw() ggplot theme. I think it looks very clean, and provides a boundary that makes it easy to visually separate the plot from the canvas. I also changed the font to "Times" and base_size to 15 to make the axis ticks pop out more.

  5. axis.title.x = element_text(size = 18, vjust = -2) and axis.title.y = element_text(size = 18, vjust = 2) Adjusted the size of the axis titles to make them easier to read. Also moved them further away from the plot in efforts to make the plot feel less cramped.

  6. axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12) and axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12) Made the axis tick labels larger so they are easier to read. I think that this is important so that the viewer can easily understand the coordinates in the plot.

  7. plot.title = element_text(size = 20, hjust = 0.5, vjust = 2) Made the plot title a bit larger and centered it. Also increased the distance between the plot and the title, again in efforts to make the plot look less cramped.

  8. plot.caption = element_text(size = 9, vjust = -5) Reduced the size of the caption so it doesnt interfere with the axis title. Also moved the caption down on the canvas for the same reason.

  9. plot.margin = unit(c(0.2, 0.2, 0.2, 0.2), "inches") Increased the plot margins so that it takes up a greater proportion of the canvas. This can be useful in improving the readability of the graph.
